type="local"
href="marcelofiore.xml"
addr="marcelofiore"
title="Marcelo Fiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00K7.xml"
addr="jms-00K7"
title="Partial function">partial function</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\mathbin {\rightharpoonup } B]]></fr:tex> is called <fr:em><fr:strong>total</fr:strong></fr:em> whenever its <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KB.xml"
addr="jms-00KB"
title="Domain of definition of a partial function">domain of definition</fr:link> coincides with its domain (source), i.e. we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f{\mathopen {}\left (a\right )\mathclose {}}{\downarrow }]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex>. In this case, we will write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\to  B]]></fr:tex> and refer to it as a <fr:em><fr:strong>function</fr:strong></fr:em> or a <fr:em><fr:strong>map</fr:strong></fr:em>. Sometimes, we redundantly refer to it as a <fr:em><fr:strong>total function</fr:strong></fr:em>.</fr:p><fr:p>Just as we write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {Rel}{\mathopen {}\left (A,B\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (A\mathbin {\rightharpoonup } B\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>for the sets of <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00I7.xml"
addr="jms-00I7"
title="Relation">relations</fr:link> and <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00K7.xml"
addr="jms-00K7"
title="Partial function">partial functions</fr:link> from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> respectively, we shall write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (A\to  B\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> for the set of functions from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
