href="marcelofiore.xml"
addr="marcelofiore"
title="Marcelo Fiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00I7.xml"
addr="jms-00I7"
title="Relation">relation</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R\colon  A\mathbin {\nrightarrow } B]]></fr:tex> is said to be <fr:em><fr:strong>functional</fr:strong></fr:em> when it relates an element of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:em>at most</fr:em> one element of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p><fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[  \forall  a\in  A\mathpunct {.}  \forall  b_1,b_2\in  B\mathpunct {.}  a\mathrel {R}b_1\land  a\mathrel {R}b_2  \implies   b_1 = b_2 ]]></fr:tex><fr:p>We refer to a functional <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00I7.xml"
addr="jms-00I7"
title="Relation">relation</fr:link> as a <fr:em><fr:strong>partial function</fr:strong></fr:em>; we often use letters like <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f,g]]></fr:tex> to refer to partial functions rather than <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R,S]]></fr:tex>. When we write <html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
style="white-space: nowrap">“<fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\to  B]]></fr:tex>”</html:span>, we mean that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is a partial function from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
